  "prompt": "What is derivation Of E=mc^2?",
  "response": "The derivation of E=mc\u00b2 is rooted in Einstein's special relativity theory. Here's a simplified overview:\n\n1. Starting Point:\n- Einstein realized that mass and energy are interconnected\n- Traditional kinetic energy formula was insufficient to explain high-speed phenomena\n\n2. Key Concepts:\n- Special relativity shows that mass increases with velocity\n- Energy and mass are different forms of the same fundamental quantity\n\n3. Mathematical Steps:\n- Consider an object's total energy at rest\n- Incorporate relativistic mass formula\n- Use Lorentz transformations\n- Analyze momentum and energy relationships\n\n4. Derivation Process:\n- Start with relativistic energy equation: E\u00b2 = (mc\u00b2)\u00b2 + (pc)\u00b2\n- At rest, momentum (p) = 0\n- Simplify to E = mc\u00b2\n\n5. Implications:\n- Even a small amount of mass contains enormous energy\n- Mass can be converted to energy and vice versa\n- Explains nuclear reactions and energy generation\n\n6. Experimental Verification:\n- Nuclear reactions\n- Particle physics experiments\n- Atomic bomb and nuclear power\n\nThe full mathematical derivation requires advanced physics and calculus, but this provides a conceptual understanding of how E=mc\u00b2 was developed.",
